  "prompt": "Is mercury a radioactive element?",
  "response": "Mercury is **not considered a radioactive element** in its most common, naturally occurring form. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n### **Natural Mercury**\n- **Symbol:** Hg\n- **Atomic Number:** 80\n- **Stable Isotopes:** Mercury has **seven stable isotopes** (from ^196Hg to ^204Hg). These isotopes are not radioactive and do not undergo radioactive decay under normal conditions.\n- **Occurrence:** Naturally occurring mercury primarily consists of these stable isotopes, making elemental mercury (the liquid metal at room temperature) non-radioactive.\n\n### **Radioactive Isotopes of Mercury**\nWhile the naturally occurring forms of mercury are stable, **there are several radioactive isotopes of mercury**, but they are typically **synthetic** and **not found in significant amounts in nature**. Some of these include:\n\n- **^194Hg**\n- **^197Hg**\n- **^198Hg**\n- **^199Hg**\n- **^200Hg**\n- **^201Hg**\n- **^202Hg**\n- **^203Hg**\n- **^204Hg** (though ^204Hg is also stable)\n\nThese radioactive isotopes are usually produced in nuclear reactors or particle accelerators and have varying half-lives, ranging from fractions of a second to several hours or days. They are primarily of interest in scientific research and have limited practical applications.\n\n### **Health and Safety**\n- **Stable Mercury:** Even though stable mercury isn't radioactive, it is **toxic** and can pose serious health risks if ingested, inhaled, or absorbed through the skin.\n- **Radioactive Mercury Isotopes:** The radioactive forms of mercury are even more hazardous due to their radioactivity, necessitating strict handling and disposal procedures to prevent contamination and exposure.\n\n### **Conclusion**\nIn summary, **elemental mercury as found in nature is not radioactive**, but some of its isotopes **are radioactive**, though these are typically man-made and not commonly encountered outside of specialized settings.",
